<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-290-717  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 290 717.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Jan 30 1989 n298 p55(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>X.400, MHS link dissimilar E-Mail: natural allies set forth basicE-Mail connectivity. (Message Handling Service)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Breidenbach, Susan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Action Technologies Inc's Message Handling Service (MHS) softwareand the International Telephone and Telegraph ConsultingCommittee's proposed X.400 messaging standard can be used togetherto bring transparent wide-area communications to users inheterogeneous computing environments.andP;  MHS provides developerswith an application programming interface that can be used tocommunicate with other applications, relieves developers fromhaving to deal with low-level programming issues and allows thefiles being delivered to initiate computing activities.andP;  The twotechnologies are different in that X.400 focuses on specifying howmessages will be moved from one point to another while MHS goesinto the organization of the documents being sent; X.400 requiresan X.25 network while MS can use asynchronous dial-up lines; andX.400's application programming interface features are defined,while developers can add any features to MHS.andP;  Popularapplications that do or will support MHS are noted.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Message Handling Service (Computer network software).andO;Topic:     ApplicationsConnectivityElectronic Mail SystemsX.400 ProtocolNetworksFunctional Capabilities.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>